g.text: Let us discuss the three most frequent causes of Data Leakage that can happen during the data collection and preparation
Target is a Function of a Feature
Imagine you train a model to predict the yearly salary of an employee, given his attributes.
The training data contains, among many other attributes, both monthly and yearly salary.
If you forget to remove the monthly salary, that attribute alone will perfectly predict the yearly salary.
Is the model perfect? Far from it..
Once the model is put in production, it will likely stop receiving info about a person's monthly salary
Sometimes the target is not a function of one or more feature, but rather it is "hidden" in one of the features
It is a kind of data leakage that is hard to catch if you do not have a clear understanding of the business goal
Imagine a client asked you to train a model that predicts whether a borrower will pay back the loan, based on
attributes such as age, gender, education, salary, marital status, and so on.
In the production environment, the value of Late Payment Reminders is always zero
The client uses our model BEFORE the borrower gets the credit, so no reminders have yet been made!
